Events*1284 ;ndash; The Republic of Pisa is defeated in the Battle of Meloria by the Republic of Genoa, thus losing its naval dominance in the Mediterranean.*1506 ;ndash; The Grand Duchy of Lithuania defeated the Crimean Khanate in the Battle of Kletsk*1538 ;ndash; Bogotá, Colombia, is founded by Gonzalo Jiménez de Quesada.*1661 ;ndash; The Treaty of The Hague is signed by Portugal and the Dutch Republic.*1777 ;ndash; American Revolutionary War: The bloody Battle of Oriskany prevents American relief of the Siege of Fort Stanwix.*1787 ;ndash; Sixty proof sheets of the Constitution of the United States are delivered to the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.*1806 ;ndash; Francis II, the last Holy Roman Emperor, abdicates, ending the Holy Roman Empire.*1819 ;ndash; Norwich University is founded in Vermont as the first private military school in the United States.*1824 ;ndash; Battle of Junín Peru.*1825 ;ndash; Bolivia gains independence from Spain.*1861 ;ndash; The United Kingdom annexes Lagos, Nigeria.*1862 ;ndash; American Civil War: The Confederate ironclad Arkansas is scuttled on the Mississippi River after suffering catastrophic engine failure near Baton Rouge, Louisiana.*1870 ;ndash; Franco-Prussian War: The Battle of Spicheren is fought, resulting in a Prussian victory.*  1870   ;ndash; Franco-Prussian War: The Battle of Wörth results in a decisive Prussian victory.*1890 ;ndash; At Auburn Prison in New York, murderer William Kemmler becomes the first person to be executed by electric chair.*1901 ;ndash; Kiowa land in Oklahoma is opened for white settlement, effectively dissolving the contiguous reservation.*1912 ;ndash; The Bull Moose Party meets at the Chicago Coliseum.*1914 ;ndash; World War I: First Battle of the Atlantic: Two days after the United Kingdom had declared war on Germany over the German invasion of Belgium, ten German U-boats leave their base in Heligoland to attack Royal Navy warships in the North Sea.*  1914   ;ndash; World War I: Serbia declares war on Germany; Austria declares war on Russia.*1915 ;ndash; World War I: Battle of Sari Bair: The Allies mount a diversionary attack timed to coincide with a major Allied landing of reinforcements at Suvla Bay.*1917 ;ndash; World War I: Battle of Mărășești between the Romanian and German armies begins.*1926 ;ndash; Gertrude Ederle becomes the first woman to swim across the English Channel.*  1926   ;ndash; In New York City, the Warner Bros.' Vitaphone system premieres with the movie ''Don Juan'' starring John Barrymore.*1930 ;ndash; Judge Joseph Force Crater steps into a taxi in New York and disappears never to be seen again.*1940 ;ndash; Estonia was illegally annexed by the Soviet Union.*1942 ;ndash; Queen Wilhelmina of the Netherlands becomes the first reigning queen to address a joint session of the United States Congress.*1944 ;ndash; The Warsaw Uprising occurs on August 1. It is brutally suppressed and all able-bodied men in Kraków are detained afterwards to prevent a similar uprising, the Kraków Uprising (1944)|Kraków Uprising, that was planned but never carried out.*1945 ;ndash; World War II: Hiroshima, Japan is devastated when the atomic bomb "Little Boy" is dropped by the United States B-29 ''Enola Gay''. Around 70,000 people are killed instantly, and some tens of thousands die in subsequent years from burns and radiation poisoning.*1956 ;ndash; After going bankrupt in 1955, the American broadcaster DuMont Television Network makes its final broadcast, a boxing match from St. Nicholas Arena in New York in the ''Boxing from St. Nicholas Arena'' series.*1960 ;ndash; Cuban Revolution: Cuba nationalizes American and foreign-owned property in the nation.*1962 ;ndash; Jamaica becomes independent from the United Kingdom.*1964 ;ndash; Prometheus, a bristlecone pine and the world's oldest tree, is cut down.*1965 ;ndash; US President Lyndon B. Johnson signs the Voting Rights Act of 1965 into law.*1976 ;ndash; Zulfikar Ali Bhutto lays the foundation stone of Port Qasim, Karachi.*1986 ;ndash; A low-pressure system that redeveloped off the New South Wales coast dumps a record 328 millimeters (13inches) of rain in a day on Sydney, New South Wales, Australia.*1988 ;ndash; The Tompkins Square Park Riot in New York City spurs a reform of the NYPD, held responsible for the event.*1990 ;ndash; Gulf War: The United Nations Security Council orders a global trade embargo against Iraq in response to Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.*1991 ;ndash; Tim Berners-Lee releases files describing his idea for the World Wide Web. WWW debuts as a publicly available service on the Internet.*  1991   ;ndash; Takako Doi, chair of the Social Democratic Party, becomes Japan's first female speaker of the House of Representatives.*1996 ;ndash; NASA announces that the ALH 84001 meteorite, thought to originate from Mars, contains evidence of primitive life-forms.*1997 ;ndash; Korean Air Flight 801 crashed at Nimitz Hill, Guam killing 228 of 254 people on board.;;*2001 ;ndash; Erwadi fire incident, 28 mentally ill persons tied to chain were burnt to death at a faith based institution at Erwadi, Tamil Nadu.*2008 ;ndash; A military junta led by Mohamed Ould Abdel Aziz stages a 2008 Mauritanian coup d'état|coup d'état in Mauritania, overthrowing president Sidi Ould Cheikh Abdallahi.*2010 ;ndash; Flash floods across a large part of Jammu and Kashmir, India, damages 71 towns and kills at least 255 people.*2011 ;ndash; A march in protest of the death of Mark Duggan in Tottenham, London, ends in a riot, sparking off a wave of rioting throughout the country over the following four nights.*  2011   ;ndash; War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|War in Afghanistan: A United States military helicopter is shot down, killing 30 American special forces members and a working dog, 7 Afghan soldiers, and 1 Afghan civilian. It was the deadliest single event for the United States in the War in Afghanistan.*2012 ;ndash; NASA's Curiosity rover lands on the surface of Mars.*2015 ;ndash; A suicide bomb attack kills at least 15 people at a mosque in the south-western Saudi city of Abha.Births*1180 ;ndash; Emperor Go-Toba of Japan (d. 1239)*1504 ;ndash; Matthew Parker, English archbishop (d. 1575)*1609 ;ndash; Richard Bennett, English-American politician, Colonial Governor of Virginia (d. 1675)*1619 ;ndash; Barbara Strozzi, Italian singer-songwriter (d. 1677)*1638 ;ndash; Nicolas Malebranche, French priest and philosopher (d. 1715)*1644 ;ndash; Louise de La Vallière, French mistress of Louis XIV of France (d. 1710)*1656 ;ndash; Claude de Forbin, French general (d. 1733)*1666 ;ndash; Maria Sophia of Neuburg (d. 1699)*1697 ;ndash; Charles VII, Holy Roman Emperor (d. 1745)*1715 ;ndash; Luc de Clapiers, marquis de Vauvenargues, French author (d. 1747)*1765 ;ndash; Petros Mavromichalis, Greek general and politician, 2nd Prime Minister of Greece (d. 1848)*1766 ;ndash; William Hyde Wollaston, English chemist and physicist (d. 1828)*1768 ;ndash; Jean-Baptiste Bessières, French general and politician (d. 1813)*1775 ;ndash; Daniel O'Connell, Irish lawyer and politician, Lord Mayor of Dublin (d. 1847)*1809 ;ndash; Alfred, Lord Tennyson, English poet and author (d. 1892)*1826 ;ndash; Thomas Alexander Browne, English-Australian author (d. 1915)*1844 ;ndash; Alfred, Duke of Saxe-Coburg and Gotha (d. 1900)*  1844   ;ndash; James Henry Greathead, South African-English engineer (d. 1896)*1846 ;ndash; Anna Haining Bates, Canadian-American giant (d. 1888)*1861 ;ndash; Edith Roosevelt, American wife of Theodore Roosevelt, 27th First Lady of the United States (d. 1948)*1868 ;ndash; Paul Claudel, French poet and playwright (d. 1955)*1874 ;ndash; Charles Fort, American author (d. 1932)*1877 ;ndash; Wallace H. White, Jr., American lawyer and politician (d. 1952)*1880 ;ndash; Hans Moser, Austrian actor and singer (d. 1964)*1881 ;ndash; Leo Carrillo, American actor, singer, and cartoonist (d. 1961)*  1881   ;ndash; Alexander Fleming, Scottish biologist, pharmac